        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Rev &amp; dear Sir:</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Yours from yesterday came<lb/> duly on hand, and in reply to the
                same<lb/> I have to state that in regard of <persName>Rabbi<lb/> Yechiel
                    Hakohen</persName> I have send a letter al–<lb/>ready to <persName>Jos M.
                    Ash</persName>, Esq. viz<lb/>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">That he must not accept the evil<lb/> report at all, nor any portion
                of it. The<lb/> report which I have heard was about <persName>Mosca<lb/>
                    Suzi</persName>Mosca<lb/> Suzi, a Meshulach* according to his own<lb/>
                statement. <persName>Rabbi Yechiel</persName> said that it is true<lb/> that he was
                a Meshulach sometime ago but is<lb/> that no longer. The above named <persName>Rabbi
                    Moses</persName>,<lb/> however showed me a letter from one of the men<lb/> of
                        <placeName><hi rend="underline">Susa</hi></placeName>, whom he met here in a
                city in the South, to<lb/> the effect that <persName>Rabbi Yechiel</persName> is now
                here having<lb/> relations with one of the women of this land. I don't know<lb/> who
                is correct, but in any event I have no doubt<lb/> that this man told a lie. For, as
                I have hear<add>d</add><lb/> from <persName>Mr. Sim Abraham</persName>, who had been
                in <placeName>Jeru<lb/>salem</placeName>, this is what he said about this
                    <persName>Rabbi Yechiel</persName></p>
            <p>* a man sent from <placeName>Palestine</placeName> or from Yeshivah to <del>get
                    the</del> collect<lb/> money./</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p><add>?</add><lb/> about 1900, and when the inhabitants of<lb/>
                <placeName>Jerusalem</placeName> were told of this they sent after<lb/> him and
                insisted that he go again to<lb/>
                <placeName>America</placeName> and they made some arrangements<lb/> with him (but I
                don't know whether <persName>Rabbi<lb/> Abraham</persName> knows anything). The
                agreement<lb/> was that he should collect money for the<lb/> building of a synagogue
                or a Beth Midrash,<lb/> and <del>they met</del> his recommendations are all<lb/>
                flattering. The impression one gets is that<lb/> they are true. That is why I
                cannot<lb/> agree to these words, which may be the<lb/> result of an “agreement”
                between <persName>Rabbi<lb/> Moses</persName> and the man from
                    <placeName>Susa</placeName> because <persName>Rabbi<lb/> Yechiel</persName> said
                something, whether true or false,<lb/> about <persName>Rabbi Moses</persName>.
                Therefore I advise<lb/> you not to pay any attention to this<lb/> matter, lest, God
                forbid, there grow out of<lb/> this matter a profanation of God's name,<lb/>
                <del>if some</del> there be truth in the matter. God knows<lb/> the hidden secrets
                of the heart and He<lb/> proves the reins and the heart and<lb/> nothing is hidden
                from him.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Whoever judges his friend leniently</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>may God come to his aid and grant<lb/> him length of days. May he leave when<lb/> the
                scattered remnants of <placeName>Israel</placeName> are<lb/> gathered together and
                    <placeName>Zion</placeName> is renewed<lb/> and <placeName>Jerusalem</placeName>
                is rebuilt Amen.<lb/> May that be God's will. From me who<lb/> writes with a broken heart.<lb/>
                <persName role="author">Simon Noht</persName>.</p>
        </body>
